==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Meliorate
<hw>Mel"io*rate</hw> <pr>(m⟦emac⟧l"y⟦osl⟧*r⟦amac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v.
t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Meliorated</conjf>
<pr>(m⟦emac⟧l"y⟦osl⟧*r⟦amac⟧`t⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Meliorating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>melioratus</ets>, p.
p. of <ets>meliorare</ets> to meliorate, fr. <ets>melior</ets> better;
akin to Gr. <grk>ma^llon</grk> rather, <grk>ma`la</grk> very. Cf.
<er>Ameliorate</er>.]</ety> <def>To make better; to improve; to
ameliorate; to soften; to make more tolerable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nature by art we nobly <qex>meliorate</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pure and benign light of revelation has had a
<qex>meliorating</qex> influence on mankind.</q>
<rj><qau>Washington.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meliorate</ent>⟦br⟧

